                <head>272. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_WH1">Wilson</persName> visited Washington
                    June 2-3, 1967, for talks with U.S. officials. According to a note on the
                    preparatory briefing books for this meeting, no formal memoranda of conversation
                    of the President’s discussions with the Prime Minister were prepared. The
                    preparatory documents for the <persName corresp="#p_WH1"
                        >Wilson</persName>-<persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName>
                    discussions are in Department of State, Visits Files: Lot 68 D 475, V-33.
                    Secretaries <persName corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName>, <persName
                        corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_FHH1"
                        >Fowler</persName> met separately with Sir <persName corresp="#p_TSB1">Burke
                        Trend</persName>, Secretary of the Cabinet, and the other members of the
                    British delegation while the President and Prime Minister met privately. The
                    discussions were dominated by a rapidly escalating crisis in the Middle East,
                    which erupted into war on June 4. Memoranda of conversation are in the Johnson
                    Library, National Security File, Country File, <gloss target="#t_UK1"
                    >UK</gloss>, Vol. 11. <persName corresp="#p_WH1">Wilson</persName> discussed his
                    meeting with the President in The Chariot of Israel, pages 346-347.</p>
            </div>
